#: ../../../user/install.rst:4
msgid "Installation of Requests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/install.rst:6
msgid ""
"This part of the documentation covers the installation of Requests. The "
"first step to using any software package is getting it properly installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/install.rst:11 ../../../user/install.rst:15
msgid "$ python -m pip install requests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/install.rst:13
msgid ""
"To install Requests, simply run this simple command in your terminal of "
"choice::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/install.rst:18
msgid "Get the Source Code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/install.rst:20
msgid ""
"Requests is actively developed on GitHub, where the code is `always "
"available <https://github.com/psf/requests>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/install.rst:23
msgid "You can either clone the public repository::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/install.rst:25
msgid "$ git clone https://github.com/psf/requests.git"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/install.rst:27
msgid ""
"Or, download the `tarball <https://github.com/psf/requests/tarball/main>`_::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/install.rst:29
msgid ""
"$ curl -OL https://github.com/psf/requests/tarball/main\n"
"# optionally, zipball is also available (for Windows users)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/install.rst:32
msgid ""
"Once you have a copy of the source, you can embed it in your own Python "
"package, or install it into your site-packages easily::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/install.rst:35
msgid ""
"$ cd requests\n"
"$ python -m pip install ."
msgstr ""
